{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474411"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:20:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12122"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12122"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.02,0.53,0.21,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96640"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4656"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-09-19T21:39:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-20T00:49:27+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-10-27T20:49:21+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-08-23 13:49:03"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12122"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"3779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2080"},{"type":"tags","id":"2932"},{"type":"tags","id":"2942"},{"type":"tags","id":"3504"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44114"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79274"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96640"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of nausea and vomiting. His parents report that he has been eating and drinking \u0022like a machine\u0022 over the previous few weeks. He has also been urinating more frequently. He had a recent upper respiratory tract infection with a runny nose and sore throat. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.7\u00b0C. His breath has a fruity odour. Investigations reveal a random blood glucose level of 21 mmol/L and urine dipstick positive for ketones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the leading cause of mortality in patients with this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute renal failure","Pulmonary oedema","Cerebral oedema","Hypokalaemia","Rhabdomyolysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral oedema\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of paediatric death associated with diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA). This phenomenon has been reporting as occurring in up to 1% of all cases of DKA however accounts for approximately 60-90% of all paediatric DKA deaths. It was thought that aggressive fluid resuscitation would produce rapidly declining serum osmolarity causing a fluid influx into the brain however the FLUID trial in 2018 suggests that the sodium changes may be a late effect of cerebral injury rather than a causation. Current monitoring of sodium, glucose and neurological observations are still recommended nonetheless.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute renal failure\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in severe DKA due to dehydration and hypoperfusion, but it is rarely a direct cause of mortality in paediatric patients. The kidney injury is typically reversible with appropriate fluid resuscitation and management of the underlying DKA. While it can contribute to morbidity, it is not considered a leading cause of death in children with DKA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary oedema\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare complication of paediatric DKA cases. As a result, some children can become hypoxic requiring ventilatory support. The pathophysiology of the oedema is thought to be due to a decrease in capillary colloid osmotic pressure during excessive intravenous fluid treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypokalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a well-known cause of complications in DKA caused by osmotic diuresis. Guidelines for prompt recognition and management of hypokalaemia associated with DKA have seen a drastic reduction in serious complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Erhabdomyolysis\u003C/strong\u003E is more frequently associated with hyperosmolar hyperglycemic syndrome (HHS), it is also a known occurrence in DKA. The mechanism of rhabdomyolysis is believed to be secondary to electrolyte and glucose abnormalities combined with the presence of insulin. These changes may lead to increased intracellular calcium which, in turn, can activate proteases and lead to muscle cell leakage. A study of children presenting with new onset T1DM found urine myoglobinuria in 10%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Classic symptoms of new-onset type 1 diabetes include polydipsia, polyuria, and polyphagia, often with recent weight loss.","Diabetic ketoacidosis is characterised by hyperglycaemia, ketonuria, and metabolic acidosis.","Cerebral oedema is the most common cause of mortality in paediatric diabetic ketoacidosis, accounting for 60-90% of deaths."],"references":["Bialo SR, Agrawal S, Boney CM, Quintos JB. Rare complications of pediatric diabetic ketoacidosis. World J Diabetes. 2015 Feb 15;6(1):167-74. doi: 10.4239/wjd.v6.i1.167. PMID: 25685287; PMCID: PMC4317308. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4317308/","Gosmanov AR, Gosmanova EO, Kitabchi AE. Hyperglycemic Crises: Diabetic Ketoacidosis and Hyperglycemic Hyperosmolar State. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Boyce A, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com. [Updated 2021 May 9]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279052/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12122"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79274"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T14:54:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T14:54:39+10:30","number":7,"notes":"Changed \u0027Coagulopathy\u0027 distractor to \u0027Acute renal failure\u0027 and updated the explanation accordingly to provide a more relevant and plausible incorrect option in the context of diabetic ketoacidosis.","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4656"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96640"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisionGenerations","id":"18690"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https